body:
CC: @jywu-msft @sfatimar for comments

Linking some issues related to C# and OpenVINO EP:
https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/5011
https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/4945

Also, it is expected that you don't see `Microsoft.ML.OnnxRuntime` (this is cpu ep related). For your build flags, it is fine to see `Microsoft.ML.OnnxRuntime.OpenVINO` (this should contain the onnxruntime native dll with the openvino ep built-in) and `Microsoft.ML.OnnxRuntime.Managed` (this contains the ep-agnostic managed assembly).

Thanks. I have gone through both of those threads previously. The issue is different as I don't see the entry point error, but the program exits directly with the following message 
The program '[26432] TestOnnx.exe' has exited with code -1073740791 (0xc0000409).

I don't see how to catch the call, but I see that it fails in SessionsOptions.cs if I specify a device id in line 167 `            var deviceIdPinned = GCHandle.Alloc(NativeOnnxValueHelper.StringToZeroTerminatedUtf8(deviceId), GCHandleType.Pinned);
`
or if I leave it to use by default, line 170
`                 NativeApiStatus.VerifySuccess(NativeMethods.OrtSessionOptionsAppendExecutionProvider_OpenVINO(handle, pinnedDeviceIdName.Pointer));
`

thanks.

I managed to manually define targets on the OpenVINO nuget package to include the header and the correct dlls (why is this not being done automatically, though?). It's also not creating anything for any runtime except native.

Running on a C++ test app, it again fails in the AppendExecutionProvider_OpenVINO with error 
2021-04-13 20:54:30.7392617 [E:onnxruntime:test, provider_bridge_ort.cc:609 onnxruntime::ProviderLibrary::Get] Failed to load library, error code: 126
or
"SessionOptionsAppendExecutionProvider_OpenVINO: Failed to load shared library", code:126, status code 0x000001cfd592a610.

@askhade - do you know why the OpenVINO nuget package might have missed the header and the correct dlls ?

As for the failure itself, @sfatimar / @jywu-msft might have some ideas.

I'm doing some change related to this #7121. 

The "OrtSessionOptionsAppendExecutionProvider_OpenVINO" function should be totally deleted. It creates more confusion than being useful.

Hi there. I've managed to fix the issue (for C++/C# at least). the onnxruntime_providers_openvino.dll looks for ngraph and tbb related dlls which are not in the path when I try to run an application in Visual Studio. Placing these dlls in Path or in the build dir gets it working. I guess it was me trying to run things from the Visual Studio GUI instead of CLI, where the setupvars.bat script would place the path correctly (I think, I'm not sure I had managed to get that working). 

I feel like this should be setup by the nuget? I had to write my own .props and .targets file to get it to work. Not sure why the nuget is missing those when it builds. At least this may help someone who runs into similar troubles in the future. Thanks!

You have to set the openvino environment using the $INTEL_OPENVINO_DIR/bin/setupvars.bat . This will set the correct environment variables for the ORT to run. You can check these and add the vars permanently to system variables.
